  "prompt": "What is on-site ratio used by IT companies?",
  "response": "In the IT industry, the on-site to offshore ratio refers to the proportion of employees working at the client's location versus those working remotely or from an offshore location. This ratio can vary depending on the project, client requirements, and company strategy. Typical on-site to offshore ratios include:\n\n1. Common ratios:\n- 20:80 (20% on-site, 80% offshore)\n- 30:70 (30% on-site, 70% offshore)\n- 40:60 (40% on-site, 60% offshore)\n\n2. Factors influencing the ratio:\n- Project complexity\n- Client preferences\n- Communication requirements\n- Cost-effectiveness\n- Technology infrastructure\n- Skill set availability\n\n3. Benefits of different ratios:\n- Higher on-site ratio: Better communication, faster problem-solving\n- Higher offshore ratio: Lower costs, access to global talent pool\n\n4. Industry trends:\n- Increasing flexibility in remote work\n- Hybrid work models\n- Cloud-based collaboration tools\n\n5. Considerations:\n- Visa regulations\n- Time zone differences\n- Cultural compatibility\n- Technical expertise\n\nThe optimal ratio depends on specific project needs and organizational goals.",
